metadata.name: Vaporwave Dream Generator 100%code
metadata.description:
I was really looking into making a 100% generative(except for the 2 music samples) no png version of the vaporwave dreamwave generator. This is my version. Everything is made using shaders and chained in p5 using the sublibrary that i made wich you may check from this repo if you are interested : 
https://github.com/jpupper/p5shader

This has 3 chained shaders : 
1. dreamwave
2. VHS
3. rotatecolor

There are 2 synthwave music samples. This music samples are postprocessing with tone.js chaining this effects : 
1. Reverb
2. Feedback Delay
3. Autowaw.

Also the playerrate is randomize. 

Interaction: 
-Click on the screen to let the music start. 
-iterated through each buffer by pressing 1 , 2 and 3 buttons. 

Thanks to kali for the rotate color shader and also for helping me with the road and the mountains.

metadata.name: Shadow Blocks - RGBPL
metadata.description:
Interactive 3D light sculpture
- Click/drag to rotate
- Scroll/pinch to zoom

Three point lights (Red, Green and Blue) hover over a canvas filled with randomly positioned cube blocks. Each light brightens the canvas and projects shadows behind each block. Other three colors (Yellow, Magenta and Cyan) emerge because of the additive property of light.

Shadow Blocks was created inspired by the sculptures made by Charles Biederman (see _Structurist Relief, Red Wing Number 1, 1958_) and the exploration of light by Olafur Eliasson (see _Your uncertain shadow (colour), 2010_).

by @code2pixels
March, 2022

Made with three.js

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

--------

WARNING

This work is GPU intensive. 

You can change render quality by pressing from 1 to 5. 1 being the lowest resolution and 5 for the best viewing experience at the cost of your GPU power/memory. 

Default render quality is 3.

You can press 's' to toggle FPS stats on screen.

Blocks Orientation

FUNCTIONALITIES

Home Camera

- Press 'a' to turn on all lights

FPS Stats

metadata.name: [Non]Sense
metadata.description:
[Non]Sense

Can words selected solely by their physical size (width and height) form a meaningful sentence? Can a phrase made up of words inscribed in certain frames carry sense or only nonsense?

Each poster in the collection is created in two stages. At the first stage, the algorithm forms a limited area from a sequence of graphic fields, with random height and width values. At the second stage, for each field, a word is selected that fits it in size. This happens as follows: first, out of 50,000 words, those words are selected whose width&height are close to the width&height of the field, then one random word is picked from them. There are no other conditions for selecting words in the algorithm.

Can it happen that with such a choice of words a meaningful phrase or sentence will turn out? Would such boundaries and limitations create sense?

Each work of the project is an experiment, it is 100% unique and is formed by an algorithm without the use of bitmap images. 

The endless variety of pieces in the collection is created by:
ðŸ“Œ  generating textures using an algorithm;
ðŸ“Œ  using a database of 50,000 words;
ðŸ“Œ  11 color palettes;
ðŸ“Œ  5 sets of fonts.

Press 's' key in live mode to save a high-resolution PNG file.

metadata.name: Swimmer
metadata.description:
I am interested in the eye getting caught in an ambiguous shape that can remind you a fish or a jellyfish, a buffalo or a crazy hairy dog, a mollusk or a protozoan, a dragon or an entity from another dimension.
I am interested in your eyes going through the figure, riding with it, and having fun in the reverie of possibilities that travels to nowhere.

The code, made in P5js, has random factors that define the texture of the background, the vertical amplitude of the movement, the length of the hair or the colors, that can be on black and white, pastel range, variable colors or variable colors with stripes.

By Diego de los Campos 2022
NFT License 2.0

metadata.name: Flipping Tiles
metadata.description:
"Flipping Tiles" contains classic tile patterns that are animated to change their colors and tile shapes. Randomness is introduced via grid size (12 options), color scheme (8 options), shape combination (3 options), and animation speed (4 options). 42 editions are available to mint.

These are my first experiments with JavaScript and P5.js, and likewise my first NFTs published on Tezos. Previously, I have been creating generative art with Python on the Polygon blockchain.

metadata.name: Shredded Memories
metadata.description:
"Shredded Memories" is the first collection released as a part of NeoMent's "Abandoned Reality" series.

Could we perfectly reconstruct something from shards? Perfectly recollect an event, that happened in the past, even to the tiny details? No. We will always try and fill in the empty spaces using our imagination. Not a single person has the same memory as you, everybody remembers differently.
The question is - how do you figure out which one is true?

metadata.name: landscrape
metadata.description:
landscrape ::: 

::: this drawing began whilst reading about Ukrainian Rushnyk cryptogram textiles as a response to hearing about this region during these difficult times 

::: a Rushnyk is a traditional woven and embroidered cloth; my starting point was the Ukrainian versions via https://web.archive.org/web/20160522145927/http://www.ukrainianmuseumdetroit.org/textiles/rushnyky.html (Rushnyk's are also found in other places)

::: I didn't want to appropriate or represent it or the traditional patterns and forms accurately, so I used the rectangular format of the cloth to represent a life's journey, and started with red as one of the main colours to represent life/health, and black for the earth

::: a cryptogram was/is used to encrypt information visually, much like art, it has visual language to carry meaning

::: after more reflection and adjusting of the drawing, it began to appear to me as an aerial view of the land, and its often-changing borders throughout history, and the patterns and forms for how people move across the land ::: landscrape

::: this is an experimental work ::: some parts are static, and some change over time, to represent movement. sometimes the changes are quite subtle, other times more pronounced

::: preview may differ slightly from main image wrt scale

metadata.name: Wandering Nets
metadata.description:
Wandering Nets is a digital kinetic light sculpture by Matt Ebb.

Networks of light are created and connected via random walks in space and colour. Emergent structures are revealed by the ambient interaction, tension and collision of these networks within themselves and orbiting shadowed spherical bodies.

The piece is the result of several months of custom development in realtime volume rendering. The scene data is generated in javascript and rendered with a bespoke GLSL raytracer - no external libraries are used.

This is a graphically intensive shader. By default it will adaptively adjust sampling quality to target 30fps, though a reasonably fast GPU is recommended for best results. 

Mouse drag: Orbit the camera in 3D to explore compositions
[ and ] keys: Override the adaptive samples per pixel lower or higher to trade noise for framerate

March 2022

metadata.name: uncurated_pico_punks.p8
metadata.description:
pico_punks is a community-curated, shared royalty, generative pfp project on the Tezos blockchain, developed on the Pico-8 Fantasy Console. Each pico_punk is uniquely generated purely from code, by displaying p8scii characters on the screen.

This fx(hash) pico_punk generator is based on "pico_punk_generator.p8" and "pico_punks_infinite.p8". It has a 50% chance to use either generator as a base. Each has been modified to permit any combination of Pico-8 colors.

The full set of curated pico_punks can be found here: https://versum.xyz/board/8Dt3fAfO8

For more pico_punks, follow @pico_punks on twitter!

metadata.name: KAO
metadata.description:
KAO is a creation of a random shape where the position of the vertices are randomly picked using cosinus, sinus, and PI number. There are also picked based on a random noise who is generated thanks to the fxhash.

Therefore, I was able to create a chaotic visual where the color of the stroke is randomly picked in high light values using HSL colors.

This project has been created using p5.js. The name KAO refers to the chaos.

metadata.name: Spiraling
metadata.description:
Look inside of you. What do you feel? What do you say to people when they ask "How's it going?"

There are 3 variations for Spiraling. I call them phases. 

Phase 1 is the most common and has a 70% chance of occurring. This phase is typically fuzzy on the inside and slightly unstable on the outside. 

Phase 2 has a 20% chance of occurring. This phase is the most unstable. 

Phase 3 is the one shown in the preview and has a 10% chance of occurring. It is typically very zen on the inside, and slightly unstable on the outside. 

Each token generates a series of 180 circles using both random values and a noise map based on the base hash.

metadata.name: Squiggly lines
metadata.description:
8192x8192px Vanilla Js

Generative painting

The drawing is based on a unique algorithm that controls a bunch of lines painting in the canvas following polar orientation rules which change direction over time and vary colors or jump to other locations all set by several features.

Features

- Color Palette: Chinese dragon,Plant based,Flesh,Lucid,Black & White,Ukraine
- Duplication: Medium, Strong
- Jump: Often, regular, rarely
- Line Length: Short, Medium, Long
- Symmetry: Diagonal, Horizontal, Vertical
- Turning probability: Little, average, a lot
- Variation: Weak, average, strong

In live mode:

- Press [s] or [double tap] to save a 8192x8192px png
- Press [p] to replay animation

metadata.name: RayCasting
metadata.description:
Ray casting is the most basic of many computer graphics rendering algorithms that use the geometric algorithm of ray tracing. Ray tracing-based rendering algorithms operate in image order to render three-dimensional scenes to two-dimensional images. Geometric rays are traced from the eye of the observer to sample the light (radiance) travelling toward the observer from the ray direction. The speed and simplicity of ray casting comes from computing the color of the light without recursively tracing additional rays that sample the radiance incident on the point that the ray hit.
This series of NFT was made so that you could take an active part in the process of consuming your NFT. Go ahead, walk around.

metadata.name: Sorting the block-chain
metadata.description:
A grid of random squares is generated and each square is assigned one of three colors. A visual sorter begins to swap squares to sort the colors into effectively three color columns. 
10 color sets
50% chance to glitch sort (3d effect)
Clear color set that always glitches

Press 'r' to reset the sort. Click/tap to pause (hides currently swapping tiles)
